\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. N. glauca} R.C. Graham,{\i  Edinb. New Philos. Jour.}{\b  5}: 175 (1828). Glabrous shrub (1-)2-6(-10) m. Leaves 5-25 cm, elliptical to lanceolate or ovate, acute, glaucous; petiole not winged. Flowers numerous in a lax panicle. Calyx 10-15 mm, tubular; teeth triangular, acute, equal. Corolla (25-)30-40 (-45) mm, tubular, yellow; limb 2-4 mm, with short lobes. Stamens subequal, inserted in basal ¼ of corolla-tube.{\i  Capsule 7-10 mm, ellipsoid. Cultivated for ornament and widely naturalized on rocks, walls and roadsides in the Mediterranean region and Portugal.} [ ?Bl Co Cr Ga Gr Hs It Lu Sa Si.] ({\i Argentina, Bolivia.})
