\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 153.          BUDDLEJACEAE}
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc Edit. †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Trees, shrubs or rarely herbs with small, sessile or stipitate glands and usually stellate hairs. Leaves opposite, very rarely alternate, simple. Flowers actinomorphic or weakly zygomorphic, usually 4-merous. Disk small or absent. Stamens epipetalous, alternating with the corolla-lobes. Ovary superior or rarely semi-inferior, 2-locular; ovules numerous; placentation axile. Style 1. Fruit a capsule.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  In addition to the species described below,{\b  Buddleja alternifolia} Maxim.,{\i  Bull. Acad. Imp. Sci. Pétersb.}{\b  26}: 494 (1880), and{\b  B. globosa} J. Hope, {\i Verh. Holland. Maatsch. Wetensch. Haarlem}{\b  20}({\b 2}): 417 (1782), are commonly cultivated and may become naturalized. The former, from China, has alternate leaves and lilac flowers in sessile axillary clusters borne on the previous year's wood. The latter, from Chile and Peru, has opposite leaves and orange flowers in long-pedunculate globose heads.
